HPI:
Mr. Smith is a 68-year-old African-American gentleman with past medical history of COPD with chronic respiratory failure on 3 L oxygen at home, hypertension, hyperlipidemia, CVA, hepatitis C who presented to the emergency department with shortness of breath and wheezing. Patient reported that he was out at a house partying all night drinking alcohol and smoking marijuana. He took his oxygen with him but he ran out.. His caregiver went to his house this morning and as he was not they are she called police and later they went to his mother's house and found out that he was at a house for a party. When they went to get him he was feeling short of breath which is why they brought him to the ER.
Hospital course:
On presentation chest x-ray was done which did not show any acute abnormalities. Patient was hemodynamically stable. Saturating well on nasal cannula. Urine cocaine screen was positive. Patient was admitted for COPD exacerbation. Started on Solu-Medrol 80 mg 3 times daily, DuoNeb every 4 hours scheduled, Symbicort.
Patient is complaining of cough while eating and he thinks that the food is going through the wrong pipe. Patient is kept n.p.o. and speech therapy was consulted.
1. COPD with acute exacerbation:
-Symptoms improved
-Received Solu-Medrol in the hospital. Continue prednisone 40 mg daily for 3 more days. Continue azithromycin for 3 more days. Continue ProAir and Advair.
2. Acute kidney injury: Resolved.
-Creatinine normalized.
3. Acute on chronic respiratory failure with hypoxia:
-Secondary to COPD exacerbation.
-Patient uses 3 L oxygen at home. Currently on 3 L and is saturating well.
4. Chest pain:
-Resolved.
-Echocardiogram was normal. Continue aspirin.
5. Iron deficiency anemia:
-Iron level is low. Started on iron supplements.
6. Hypertension:
-Controlled.
-Continue amlodipine 10 mg daily, losartan 100 mg daily.
7. Alcohol abuse:
-On DT prophylaxis protocol in the hospital.
-Continue thiamine, folic acid. Prescriptions given.
- Counseled.
8. Dysphagia:
-Patient complained of aspiration.
-Speech therapy consulted. Did well on swallow evaluation. Recommended soft diet and to avoid rice, grains or popcorn.
9. BPH:
-Continue tamsulosin and finasteride.
10. GERD:
-Continue Protonix.
Patient was seen and examined on the day discharge. Plan of care was discussed with the patient. Total time spent was 25 minutes.
